# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ac-adapter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:ac-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] An **adapter** or **adaptor** is a device that converts attributes of one electrical device or system to those of an otherwise incompatible device or system.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Some modify power or signal attributes, while others merely adapt the physical form of one connector to another.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Many countries with ties to Europe use 230-volt, 50 Hz AC mains electricity, using a variety of power plugs and sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Difficulty arises when moving an electrical device between countries that use different sockets.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] A passive electric power adapter, sometimes called a *travel plug* or *travel adapter*, allows using a plug from one region with a foreign socket.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] As other countries supply 120-volt, 60 Hz AC, using a travel adapter in a country with a different supply poses a safety hazard if the connected device does not support both input voltages.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] An AC-to-DC power supply adapts electricity from household mains voltage (either 120 or 230 volts AC) to low-voltage DC suitable for powering consumer electronics.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Small, detached power supplies for consumer electronics are called *AC adapters*, or variously *power bricks*, *wall warts*, or *chargers*.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] A *host controller* connects a computer to a peripheral device, such as a storage device, network, or human interface device.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] As a host controller can also be viewed as bridging the protocols used on the buses between peripheral and computer, and internally to the computer, it is also called a *host bus adapter*.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Likewise, specific types may be called adapters: a network interface controller may be called a *network adapter*, and a graphics card a *display adapter*.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Adapters (often in the form of *dongles*) allow connecting a peripheral device with one plug to a different jack on the computer.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] They are often used to connect modern devices to a legacy port on an old system, or old devices to a modern port.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Such adapters may be entirely passive, or contain active circuitry.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] One kind of serial port adapter enables connections between 25-contact and nine-contact connectors, but does not affect electrical power- and signalling-related attributes.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] HDMI is backward compatible with the single-channel digital video interface (DVI-D or DVI-I, but not DVI-A or dual-channel DVI).
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] When using an adapter or an asymmetric cable, no signal conversion is required, so video quality is not lost. “This means that DVI can be connected to an HDMI input using an adapter.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] DVI was an important step forward, introducing digital video.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] A separate cable to the audio output on the computer or sound card was required for that.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Any DVI-HDMI adapter can function as an HDMI-DVI adapter (and vice versa).
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Usually, the only limitation is the gender of the adapter connectors, as well as the gender of cables and connectors with which it is used.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Features characteristic of HDMI, such as remote control and audio transmission, are not available on devices using the legacy DVI-D signal.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] However, many devices output HDMI via a DVI connector (for example, ATI 3000 series and NVIDIA GTX 200 graphics cards), and some multimedia displays can accept HDMI (including audio) through a DVI input.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] The exact capabilities beyond basic compatibility may vary.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Adapters and active converters are also available for connecting HDMI to other video interfaces, including older analog formats as well as digital formats such as DisplayPort.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Introduced in the 2000s, DisplayPort was designed to replace older standards such as VGA, DVI, and FPD-Link.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] Although it is not directly compatible with these formats, adapters are available for connecting to HDMI, DVI, VGA, and other interfaces.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] There are USB-CEC adapters that allow a computer to control devices supporting Consumer Electronics Control.
[src:ac-adapter/adapter] In software, an adapter is a piece of code that complies with an interface of an existing component while actually using another implementation.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:ac-adapter/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX is a commonly used motherboard and power supply hardware form factor for desktop computers.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The ATX form factor defined a general mounting point placement and I/O panel size that smaller motherboards share (such as microATX, FlexATX, and Mini-ITX), making them backwards compatible in many computer cases.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] As of 2012, ATX is the most common motherboard design.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Other standards for smaller boards (including microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, and mini-ITX) keep the basic rear layout but reduce the size of the board and the number of expansion slots.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Dimensions of a full-size ATX board are 12 × 9.6 in (305 × 244 mm) which means microATX boards fit in many ATX chassis.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The ATX specifications were patented by David Dent at Intel and co-developed with Astec America, a major manufacturer of power supplies at the time.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The inaugural version 1.0 of the ATX specification was unveiled by Intel in July 1995.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Since then, ATX has been revised numerous times.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The most recent ATX motherboard specification is version 2.2.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The most recent ATX12V power supply unit specification is ATX 3.0 released in February 2022.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] EATX, or E-ATX (Extended ATX), is a term that refers to motherboards larger than the ATX standard.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Motherboards labeled E-ATX commonly share dimensions with the SSI-EEB (Server System Infrastructure - Enterprise Electronics Bay) standard (12 x 13 in), however, it is not a guarantee.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] While some dual-CPU-socket motherboards have been implemented in ATX, the extra size of EATX makes it the typical form factor for dual-socket systems and for single-socket systems with a large number of memory slots (or more than two memory channels).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] In 2004, Intel announced the BTX (Balanced Technology eXtended) standard, intended as a replacement for ATX.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] While some manufacturers adopted the new standard, Intel discontinued any future development of BTX in 2006.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] As of 2026, the ATX design still remains the standard for personal computers.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] On the back of the computer case, some major changes were made to the AT standard.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Originally AT style cases had only a keyboard connector and expansion slots for add-on card backplates.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Any other onboard interfaces (such as serial and parallel ports) had to be connected via flying leads to connectors which were mounted either on spaces provided by the case or brackets placed in unused expansion slot positions.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The ATX standard specified a rectangular area on the back of the system where motherboard manufacturers can arrange ports any way they want.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] A number of general patterns (depending on which ports the motherboard offers) have been used by most manufacturers.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Cases are usually fitted with a snap-out panel, also known as an I/O plate or I/O shield, in one of the common arrangements.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] I/O plates are usually included with retail motherboards for installation in any suitable case.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The computer will operate correctly without a plate fitted, but there will be open gaps in the case which may compromise the EMI/RFI screening and allow the ingress of dirt and random foreign bodies.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Panels were made that fit an AT motherboard in an ATX case.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Some ATX motherboards come with an integrated I/O plate.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX also made the PS/2-style mini-DIN keyboard and mouse connectors ubiquitous.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] AT systems used a 5-pin DIN connector for the keyboard and were generally used with serial port mice (although PS/2 mouse ports were also found on some systems).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Many modern motherboards are phasing out the PS/2-style keyboard and mouse connectors in favor of the more modern Universal Serial Bus.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Other legacy connectors that are slowly being phased out of modern ATX motherboards include 25-pin parallel ports and 9-pin RS-232 serial ports.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] In their place are onboard peripheral ports such as Ethernet, FireWire, eSATA, audio ports (both analog and S/PDIF), video (analog D-sub, DVI, HDMI, or DisplayPort), extra USB ports, and Wi-Fi.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] A notable issue with the ATX specification was that it was last revised when power supplies were normally placed at the top of many old computer cases rather than at the bottom, as with many modern computer cases.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This has led to some problematic standard locations for ports, in particular the 4/8 pin CPU power, which is normally located along the top edge of the board, convenient for top-mounted power supplies.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This makes it very difficult for cables from bottom-mounted power supplies to reach, and commonly requires a special cutout in the back plane for the cable to come in from behind and bend around the board, making insertion and wire management very difficult.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Many power supply cables barely or fail to reach, or are too stiff to make the bend, and extensions are sometimes required due to this placement.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Modern power supplies often have longer cables to alleviate this issue.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Several ATX-derived designs have been specified that use the same power supply, mountings and basic back panel arrangement, but set different standards for the size of the board and number of expansion slots.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Standard ATX provides seven slots at 0.8 in (20 mm) spacing; the popular microATX size removes 2.4 inches (61 mm) and three slots, leaving four.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Here width refers to the distance along the external connector edge, while depth is from front to rear.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Note each larger size inherits all previous (smaller) colors area.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] AOpen has conflated the term Mini ATX with a more recent 15 × 15 cm (5.9 × 5.9 in) design.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Since references to Mini ATX have been removed from ATX specifications since the adoption of microATX, the AOpen definition is the more contemporary term and the one listed above is apparently only of historical significance.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This sounds contradictory to the now common Mini-ITX standard (17 × 17 cm (6.7 × 6.7 in)), which is a potential source of confusion.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] A number of manufacturers have added one to three additional expansion slots (at the standard 0.8 inch spacing) to the standard 12-inch ATX motherboard width.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Form factors considered obsolete in 1999 included Baby-AT, full size AT, and the semi-proprietary LPX for low-profile cases.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Proprietary motherboard designs such as those by Compaq, Packard-Bell, Hewlett Packard and others existed, and were not interchangeable with multi-manufacturer boards and cases.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Portable and notebook computers and some 19-inch rackmount servers have custom motherboards unique to their particular products.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] While E-ATX and SSI EEB (Server System Infrastructure (SSI) Forum's Enterprise Electronics Bay (EEB)) share the same dimensions, the screw holes of the two standards do not all align; rendering them incompatible.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] In 2008, Foxconn unveiled a Foxconn F1 motherboard prototype, which has the same width as a standard ATX motherboard, but an extended 14.4" length to accommodate 10 slots.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The firm called the new 14.4 × 9.6 in (366 × 244 mm) design of this motherboard "Ultra ATX" in its CES 2008 showing.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Also unveiled during the January 2008 CES was the Lian Li Armorsuit PC-P80 case with 10 slots designed for the motherboard.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] In 2010, EVGA Corporation released a new motherboard, the "Super Record 2", or SR-2, whose size surpasses that of the "EVGA X58 Classified 4-Way SLI".
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The new board is designed to accommodate two Dual QPI LGA1366 socket CPUs (e.g.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Intel Xeon), similar to that of the Intel Skulltrail motherboard that could accommodate two Intel Core 2 Quad processors and has a total of seven PCI-E slots and 12 DDR3 RAM slots.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The ATX specification requires the power supply to produce three main outputs, +3.3 V, +5 V and +12 V.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Low-power −12 V and +5 VSB (standby) supplies are also required.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The −12 V supply is primarily used to provide the negative supply voltage for RS-232 ports and is also used by one pin on conventional PCI slots primarily to provide a reference voltage for some models of sound cards.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The 5 VSB supply is used to produce trickle power to provide the soft-power feature of ATX when a PC is turned off, as well as powering the real-time clock to conserve the charge of the CMOS battery.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] A −5 V output was originally required because it was supplied on the ISA bus.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] However, it was removed in later versions of the ATX standard once ISA expansion slots became obsolete.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Originally, the motherboard was powered by one 20-pin connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] An ATX power supply provides a number of peripheral power connectors and (in modern systems) two connectors for the motherboard: an 8-pin (or 4+4-pin) auxiliary connector providing additional power to the CPU and a main 24-pin power supply connector, an extension of the original 20-pin version.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The connector pin pitch is 4.20 mm (about one sixth of an inch).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Generally, supply voltages must be within ±5% of their nominal values at all times.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The little-used negative supply voltages, however, have a ±10% tolerance.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The 20–24-pin Molex Mini-Fit Jr. has a power rating of, 9 amperes maximum per pin).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] As large server motherboards and 3D graphics cards have required progressively more and more power to operate, it has been necessary to revise and extend the standard beyond the original 20-pin connector, to allow more current using multiple additional pins in parallel.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The low circuit voltage is the restriction on power flow through each connector pin; at the maximum rated voltage, a single Mini-Fit Jr pin would be capable of 4800 watts.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] That last dimension, the 140 mm depth, is frequently varied, with depths of 160, 180, 200 and 230 mm used to accommodate higher power, larger fan and/or modular connectors.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Original AT cases (flat case style) have an integrated power switch that protruded from the power supply and sits flush with a hole in the AT chassis.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It utilizes a paddle-style DPST switch and is similar to the PC and PC-XT style power supplies.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Later AT (so-called "Baby AT") and LPX style computer cases have a power button that is directly connected to the system computer power supply (PSU).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The general configuration is a double-pole latching mains voltage switch with the four pins connected to wires from a four-core cable.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The wires are either soldered to the power button (making it difficult to replace the power supply if it failed) or blade receptacles were used.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] An ATX power supply is typically controlled by an electronic switch connected to the power button on the computer case and allows the computer to be turned off by the operating system.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] In addition, many ATX power supplies have a manual switch on the back that also ensures no power is being sent to the components.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] When the switch on the power supply is turned off, the computer cannot be turned on with the front power button.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX uses one large, keyed connector which can not be connected incorrectly.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The new connector also provides a 3.3 volt source, removing the need for motherboards to derive this voltage from the 5 V rail.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Some motherboards, particularly those manufactured after the introduction of ATX but whilst LPX equipment was still in use, support both LPX and ATX PSUs.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] A minimum load on one or more voltages may be required (varies by model and vendor); the standard does not specify operation without a minimum load and a conforming PSU may shut down, output incorrect voltages, or otherwise malfunction, but will not be hazardous or damaged.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] An ATX power supply is not a replacement for a current-limited bench laboratory DC power supply; instead it is better described as a bulk DC power supply.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The original ATX specification called for a power supply to be located near to the CPU with the power supply fan drawing in cooling air from outside the chassis and directing it onto the processor.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It was thought that in this configuration, cooling of the processor would be achievable without the need of an active heatsink.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This recommendation was removed from later specifications; modern ATX power supplies usually exhaust air from the case.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The power distribution specification defined that most of the PSU's power should be provided on 5 V and 3.3 V rails, because most of the electronic components (CPU, RAM, chipset, PCI, AGP and ISA cards) used 5 V or 3.3 V for power supply.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] While designing the Pentium 4 platform in 1999/2000, the standard 20-pin ATX power connector was found insufficient to meet increasing power-line requirements; the standard was significantly revised into ATX12V 1.0 (ATX12V 1.x is sometimes inaccurately called ATX-P4).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX12V 1.x was also adopted by AMD Athlon XP and Athlon 64 systems.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] However, some early model Athlon XP and MP boards (including some server boards) and later model lower-end motherboards do not have the 4-pin connector as described below.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Numbering of the ATX revisions may be a little confusing: ATX refers to the design, and goes up to version 2.2 in 2004 (with the 24 pins of ATX12V 2.0), while ATX12V describes only the PSU.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] For instance, ATX 2.03 is quite commonly seen on PSUs from 2000 and 2001 and often includes the P4 12V connector, even if the norm itself did not define it yet.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Formally called the *+12 V Power Connector*, this is commonly referred to as the **P4 connector** because this was first needed to support the Pentium 4 processor.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Before the Pentium 4, processors were generally powered from the 5 V rail.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Later processors operate at much lower voltages, typically around 1 V and some draw over 100 A.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It is infeasible to provide power at such low voltages and high currents from a standard system power supply, so the Pentium 4 established the practice of generating it with a DC-to-DC converter on the motherboard next to the processor, powered by the 4-pin 12 V connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This is a minor revision from August 2000.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The power on the 3.3 V rail was slightly increased and other smaller changes were made.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] A relatively minor revision from January 2002.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The only significant change was that the −5 V rail was no longer required (it became optional).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This voltage was required by the ISA bus, which is no longer present on almost all modern computers.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Introduced in April 2003 (a month after 2.0).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This standard introduced some changes, mostly minor.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX12V 2.x brought a significant design change regarding power distribution.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] By analyzing the power demands of then-current PCs, it was determined that it would be much cheaper and more practical to power most PC components from 12 V rails, instead of from 3.3 V and 5 V rails.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] In particular, PCI Express expansion cards take much of their power from the 12 V rail (up to 5.5 A), while the older AGP graphics cards took only up to 1 A on 12 V and up to 6 A on 3.3 V.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The CPU is also driven by a 12 V rail, while it was done by a 5 V rail on older PCs (before the Pentium 4).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This is a minor revision from June 2004.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] An errant reference for the −5 V rail was removed.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This is a minor revision from March 2005.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The power was slightly increased on all rails.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Efficiency requirements changed: minimum 65% at light load, 72% at typical load, and 70% at full load.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Introduced recommended minimum values of 75% at light load, 80% at typical load, and 77% at full load.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Also released in March 2005 it includes corrections and specifies High Current Series wire terminals for 24-pin ATX motherboard and 4-pin +12 V power connectors.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Recommended efficiency was increased to 80% (with at least 70% required) and the 12 V minimum load requirement was lowered.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Higher efficiency generally results in less power consumption (and less waste heat) and the 80% recommendation brings supplies in line with new Energy Star 4.0 mandates.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The reduced load requirement allows compatibility with processors that draw very little power during startup.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The absolute over-current limit of 240 VA per rail was removed, allowing 12 V lines to provide more than 20 A per rail.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This revision became effective in February 2008.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The ATX12V 2.4 specifications were published in August 2012.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It is specified in Revision 1.31 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors*, which names this as ATX12V version 2.4.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] In July 2012, revision 1.3 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors* made inclusion of the floppy drive connector optional, instead of mandatory.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The specifications for ATXV12 2.51 were released in September 2021 and introduced support for *Alternative Low Power Mode (ALPM)* which supersedes the traditional S3 power state.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Windows 10 implements this functionality as *Modern Standby*.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Power supply fans are also recommended to turn on with at least a two second delay for an improved user experience.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This version also stated that the floppy drive connector should be excluded from PSUs, as opposed to merely being optional, and marked that connector's section in the specification as "For Historical Reference Only".
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The specifications for ATX12V 2.53 were released in December 2021 and constitute another minor update to the ATX standard.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX12V 2.53 makes further recommendations on efficiency and references the Energy Star *Computers Specification Version 8.0* which was finalized in April 2020.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The specifications for ATX 3.0 were released in February 2022.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It includes the new 16-pin 12VHPWR connector that can deliver up to 600 W for H+ and up to 675 W in H++ to graphics cards.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] These incorporate data lines for components to negotiate power capabilities with the PSU so they do not draw more power than the PSU is capable of delivering.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The specification also has more strict requirements for handling spikes, two times the nominal output for 100 microseconds.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The −12 V supply is now specified as optional on the ATX motherboard connector, and some PSU manufacturers (e.g.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Corsair) have begun removing the −12 V supply from their PSUs.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] However, as of 2025, some motherboards (e.g. recent designs from ASRock) still use the −12 V supply - typically to power the amplifier for on-board audio - and functions that use it will not work as expected when paired with a PSU that does not provide a −12 V supply.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX 3.1 replaces the 12VHPWR power connector with the 12V-2x6 power connector and reduces required power loss hold-up time from 17 milliseconds to 12 milliseconds.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Standing for **ATX 12-volt-only**, this is a new specification published by Intel in 2019, aimed at pre-built systems in the first run, and stricter power efficiency requirements by the California Energy Commission going into effect in 2021.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Several OEMs were already using a similar design with proprietary connectors and this effectively standardizes those.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Under this standard, power supplies provide only a 12 V output.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX12VO introduces a new 10-pin connector to supply the motherboard, replacing the 24-pin ATX12V connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This greatly simplifies power supplies, but moves DC-to-DC conversion and some connectors to the motherboard instead.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Notably, SATA power connectors, which include 3.3 V and 5 V pins, need to move to the motherboard instead of being connected directly to the power supply.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Connector pinout per Intel ATX12VO (12V Only) Desktop Power Supply Design Guide.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] SFX (Small Form-Factor eXtended) is merely a design for a small form factor (SFF) power supply casing (such as those using microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, mini-ITX, and NLX), with the power specifications almost identical to ATX.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Thus, an SFX power supply is mostly pin-compatible with the ATX power supply as the main difference is its reduced dimensions; the only electrical difference is that the SFX specifications do not require the −5 V rail.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Since −5 V is required only by some ISA-bus expansion cards, this is not an issue with modern hardware and decreases productions costs.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] As a result, ATX pin 20, which carried −5 V, is absent in current power supplies; it was optional in ATX and ATX12V version 1.2 and deleted as of ATX version 1.3.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] SFX has dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 100 mm (width × height × depth), with a 60 mm fan, compared with the standard ATX dimensions of 150 × 86 × 140 mm.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Optional 80 or 40 mm fan replacement increases or decreases the height of an SFX unit.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Some manufacturers and retailers incorrectly market SFX power supplies as μATX or MicroATX power supplies.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Some manufacturers make SFX-L dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 130 mm to accommodate a 120 mm fan.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Thin Form Factor is another small power supply design with standard ATX specification connectors.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] WTX power supplies provide a WTX style motherboard connector which is incompatible with the standard ATX motherboard connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] This is an ATX12V power supply derivative made by AMD to power its Athlon MP (dual processor) platform.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It was used only on high-end Athlon MP motherboards.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It has a special 8-pin supplemental connector for motherboard, so an AMD GES PSU is required for such motherboards (those motherboards will not work with ATX(12 V) PSUs).
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX12V-GES 24-pin P1 motherboard connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] ATX12V-GES 8-pin P2 motherboard connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] EPS12V is defined in Server System Infrastructure (SSI) and used primarily by SMP/multi-core systems such as Core 2, Core i7, Opteron and Xeon.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] It has a 24-pin ATX motherboard connector (same as ATX12V v2.x), an 8-pin secondary connector and an optional 4-pin tertiary connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Rather than include the extra cable, many power supply makers implement the 8-pin connector as two combinable 4-pin connectors to ensure backwards compatibility with ATX12V motherboards.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] High-performance video card power demands dramatically increased during the 2000s and some high-end graphics cards have power demands that exceed AGP or PCIe slot capabilities.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] For these cards, supplementary power was delivered through a standard 4-pin peripheral or floppy power connector.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Midrange and high-end PCIe graphics cards manufactured after 2004 typically use a standard 6- or 8-pin PCIe power connector directly from the PSU.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Efficiency in power supplies means the extent to which power is not wasted in converting electricity from a household supply to regulated DC.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Computer power supplies vary from around 70% to over 90% efficiency.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Various initiatives exist to improve the efficiency of computer power supplies.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Climate Savers Computing Initiative promotes energy saving and reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by encouraging development and use of more efficient power supplies.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] 80 PLUS certifies a variety of efficiency levels for power supplies and encourages their use via financial incentives.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Efficient power supplies also save money by wasting less power; as a result they use less electricity to power the same computer, and they emit less waste heat which results in significant energy savings on central air conditioning in the summer.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] The gains of using an efficient power supply are more substantial in computers that use a lot of power.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Although a power supply with a larger than needed power rating will have an extra margin of safety against overloading, such a unit is often less efficient and wastes more electricity at lower loads than a more appropriately sized unit.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] Thus, for a 100 W load, losses for this supply would be 27 W; if the same power supply was put under a 450 W load, for which the supply's efficiency peaks at 89%, the loss would be only 56 W despite supplying 4.5 times the useful power.
[src:ac-adapter/atx] For a comparison, a 500-watt power supply carrying the 80 Plus Bronze efficiency rating (which means that such a power supply is designed to be at least 82-percent efficient for loads above 100 W) may provide an 84 percent efficiency for a 100 W load, wasting only 19 W.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A **battery charger**, **recharger**, or simply **charger**, is a device that stores energy in an electric battery by running current through it.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The charging protocol—how much voltage and current, for how long and what to do when charging is complete—depends on the size and type of the battery being charged.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some battery types have high tolerance for overcharging after the battery has been fully charged and can be recharged by connection to a constant voltage source or a constant current source, depending on battery type.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Simple chargers of this type must be manually disconnected at the end of the charge cycle.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Other battery types use a timer to cut off when charging should be complete.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Other battery types cannot withstand over-charging, becoming damaged (reduced capacity, reduced lifetime), over heating or even exploding.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The charger may have temperature or voltage sensing circuits and a microprocessor controller to safely adjust the charging current and voltage, determine the state of charge, and cut off at the end of charge.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Chargers may elevate the output voltage proportionally with current to compensate for impedance in the wires.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A trickle charger provides a relatively small amount of current, only enough to counteract self-discharge of a battery that is idle for a long time.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some battery types cannot tolerate trickle charging; attempts to do so may result in damage.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Lithium-ion batteries cannot handle indefinite trickle charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Slow battery chargers may take several hours to complete a charge.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] High-rate chargers may restore most capacity much faster, but high-rate chargers can be more than some battery types can tolerate.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Such batteries require active monitoring of the battery to protect it from any abusive use.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Electric vehicles ideally need high-rate chargers.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] For public access, installation of such chargers and the distribution support for them is an issue in the proposed adoption of electric cars.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Charge and discharge rates are often given as *C* or *C-rate*, which is a measure of the rate at which a battery is charged or discharged relative to its capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The C-rate is defined as the charge or discharge current divided by the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] While rarely stated explicitly, the unit of the C-rate is h−1, equivalent to stating the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge in unit hour times current in the same unit as the charge or discharge current.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The C-rate is never negative, so whether it describes a charging or discharging process depends on the context.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] For example, for a battery with a capacity of 500 mAh, a discharge rate of 5000 mA (i.e., 5 A) corresponds to a C-rate of 10C, meaning that such a current can discharge 10 such batteries in one hour.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Likewise, for the same battery a charge current of 250 mA corresponds to a C-rate of C/2, meaning that this current will increase the state of charge of this battery by 50% in one hour.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Running current through batteries generates internal heat, roughly proportional to the current involved (a battery's current state of charge, condition / history, etc. are also factors).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] If the charging process is endothermic (which is the case for Ni–Cd batteries, whereas charging nickel–metal hydride batteries is exothermic) the charging process initially cools the battery, but as it reaches full charge, the cooling effect stops and the cell heats up.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Detecting a temperature rise of 10 °C (18 °F) is one way of determining when to stop charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Battery cells which have been built to allow higher C-rates than usual must make provision for increased heating.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] But high C-ratings are attractive to end users because such batteries can be charged more quickly, and produce higher current output in use.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] High C-rates typically require the charger to carefully monitor battery parameters such as terminal voltage and temperature to prevent overcharging and so damage to the cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Such high-charging rates are possible only with some battery types.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Others will be damaged or possibly overheat or catch fire.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] For example, an automobile SLI (starting, lighting, ignition) lead–acid battery carries several risks of explosion.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A simple charger works by supplying a constant DC or pulsed DC power source to a battery being charged.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A simple charger typically does not alter its output based on charging time or the charge on the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] This simplicity means that a simple charger is inexpensive, but there are tradeoffs.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Typically, a carefully designed simple charger takes longer to charge a battery because it is set to use a lower (i.e., safer) charging rate.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Even so, many batteries left on a simple charger for too long will be weakened or destroyed due to over-charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] These chargers also vary in that they can supply either a constant voltage or a constant current, to the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Simple AC-powered battery chargers usually have much higher ripple current and ripple voltage than other kinds of battery chargers because they are inexpensively designed and built.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Generally, when the ripple current is within a battery's manufacturer recommended level, the ripple voltage will also be well within the recommended level.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The maximum ripple current for a typical 12 V 100 Ah VRLA battery is 5 amperes.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] As long as the ripple current is not excessive (more than 3 to 4 times the level recommended by the battery manufacturer), the expected life of a ripple-charged VRLA battery will be within 3% of the life of a constant DC-charged battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Fast chargers make use of control circuitry to rapidly charge the batteries without damaging any of the cells in the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The control circuitry can be built into the battery (generally for each cell) or in the external charging unit, or split between both.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Most such chargers have a cooling fan to help keep the temperature of the cells at safe levels.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Most fast chargers are also capable of acting as standard overnight chargers if used with standard Ni–MH cells that do not have the special control circuitry.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] To accelerate the charging time and provide continuous charging, an intelligent charger attempts to detect the state of charge and condition of the battery and applies a three-stage charging scheme.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The following description assumes a sealed lead–acid traction battery at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The first stage is referred to as "bulk absorption"; the charging current is held high and constant and is limited by the capacity of the charger.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] When the voltage on the battery reaches its outgassing voltage (2.22 volts per cell) the charger switches to the second stage, and the voltage is held constant (2.40 volts per cell).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The delivered current declines at the maintained voltage, and when the current reaches less than 0.005C the charger enters its third stage and the charger output is held constant at 2.25 volts per cell.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] In the third stage, the charging current is very small, 0.005C, and at this voltage the battery can be maintained at full charge and compensate for self-discharge.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers use electromagnetic induction to charge batteries.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A charging station sends electromagnetic energy through inductive coupling to an electrical device, which stores the energy in the batteries.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] This is achieved without the need for metal contacts between the charger and the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers are commonly used in electric toothbrushes and other devices used in bathrooms.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Because there are no open electrical contacts, there is no risk of electrocution.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Nowadays it is being used to charge wireless phones.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A smart charger can respond to the condition of a battery and modify its charging parameters accordingly, whereas "dumb" chargers apply a steady voltage, possibly through a fixed resistance.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] It should not be confused with a smart battery that contains a computer chip and communicates digitally with a smart charger about battery condition.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A smart battery requires a smart charger.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some smart chargers can also charge "dumb" batteries, which lack any internal electronics.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The output current of a smart charger depends upon the battery's state.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] An intelligent charger may monitor the battery's voltage, temperature or charge time to determine the optimum charge current or terminate charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] For Ni–Cd and Ni–MH batteries, the voltage of the battery increases slowly during the charging process, until the battery is fully charged.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] After that, the voltage *decreases* because of increasing temperature, which indicates to an intelligent charger that the battery is fully charged.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Such chargers are often labeled as a ΔV, "delta-V", or sometimes "delta peak" charger, indicating that they monitor voltage change.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] This can cause even an intelligent charger not to sense that the batteries are already fully charged, and continue charging, the result of which may be overcharging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Many intelligent chargers employ a variety of cut-off systems to prevent overcharging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A typical smart charger fast-charges a battery up to about 85% of its maximum capacity in less than an hour, then switches to trickle charging, which takes several hours to top off the battery to its full capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Several companies have begun making devices that charge batteries using energy from human motion, such as walking.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] An example, made by Tremont Electric, consists of a magnet held between two springs that can charge a battery as the device is moved up and down.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Such products have not yet achieved significant commercial success.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A pedal-powered charger for mobile phones fitted into desks has been created for installation in public spaces, such as airports, railway stations and universities.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] They have been installed in a number of countries on several continents.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some chargers use *pulse technology*, in which a series of electrical pulses is fed to the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The DC pulses have a strictly controlled rise time, pulse width, pulse repetition rate (frequency) and amplitude.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] This technology works with any size and type of battery, including automotive and valve-regulated ones.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] With pulse charging, high instantaneous voltages are applied without overheating the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] In a lead–acid battery, this breaks down lead-sulfate crystals, thus greatly extending the battery service life.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Several kinds of pulse chargers are patented, while others are open source hardware.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some chargers use pulses to check the current battery state when the charger is first connected, then use constant current charging during fast charge, then use pulse mode to trickle charge it.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some chargers use "negative pulse charging", also called "reflex charging" or "burp charging".
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] These chargers use both positive and brief negative current pulses.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] There is no significant evidence that negative pulse charging is more effective than ordinary pulse charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Solar chargers convert light energy into low-voltage DC current.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] They are generally portable, but can also be fixed mounted.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Fixed mount solar chargers are also known as solar panels.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] These are often connected to the electrical grid via control and interface circuits, whereas portable solar chargers are used off-grid (i.e. cars, boats, or RVs).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Although portable solar chargers obtain energy only from the sun, they can charge in low light like at sunset.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Portable solar chargers are often used for trickle charging, though some can completely recharge batteries.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The output of a timer charger is terminated after a predetermined time interval.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Timer chargers were the most common type for high-capacity Ni–Cd cells in the late 1990s to charge low-capacity consumer Ni–Cd cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Often a timer charger and set of batteries could be bought as a bundle and the charger time is set for those batteries specifically.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] If batteries of lower capacity are charged, then they would be overcharged, and if batteries of higher capacity were timer-charged, they would not reach full capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Timer based chargers also had the drawback that charging batteries that were not fully discharged would result in over-charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A trickle charger is typically low-current (usually between 5–1,500 mA).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] They are generally used to charge small capacity batteries (2–30 Ah).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] They are also used to maintain larger capacity batteries (> 30 Ah) in cars and boats.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] In larger applications, the current of the battery charger is only sufficient to provide trickle current.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Depending on the technology of the trickle charger, it can be left connected to the battery indefinitely.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some battery types are not suitable for trickle charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] For instance, most Li-ion batteries cannot be safely trickle charged and can cause a fire or explosion.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Charge DC (battery) from DC source without conversion to AC.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Modern DC-DC chargers often include isolator and DC-DC converter.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some may also have BMS (including balance), be bidirectional (jump start primary car battery from secondary battery) and wireless control (Bluetooth, WiFi, NFC, 5G).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The most sophisticated chargers are used in critical applications (e.g. military or aviation batteries).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] These heavy-duty automatic "intelligent charging" systems can be programmed with complex charging cycles specified by the battery manufacturer.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The best are universal (i.e. can charge all battery types), and include automatic capacity testing and analyzing functions.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Since the Universal Serial Bus specification provides five-volt power, it is possible to use a USB cable to connect a device to a power supply.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Products based on this approach include chargers for cellular phones, portable digital audio players, and tablet computers.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] They may be fully compliant USB peripheral devices or uncontrolled, simple chargers.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Another type of USB charger called "USB (rechargeable) battery" is fitted into the case of standard batteries (1.5 V AA, C, D, and 9 V block) together with a Li-ion rechargeable battery, voltage converter, and USB connector.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Since a battery charger is intended to be connected to a battery, it may not have voltage regulation or filtering of the DC voltage output; it is cheaper to make them that way.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Battery chargers equipped with both voltage regulation and filtering are sometimes termed battery eliminators.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Chargers for car batteries come in varying ratings.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Chargers that are rated up to two amperes may be used to maintain charge on parked vehicle batteries or for small batteries on garden tractors or similar equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A motorist may keep a charger rated a few amperes to ten or fifteen amperes for maintenance of automobile batteries or to recharge a vehicle battery that has accidentally discharged.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Service stations and commercial garages will have a large charger to fully charge a battery in an hour or two; often these chargers can briefly source the hundreds of amperes required to crank an internal combustion engine starter.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Electric vehicle battery chargers (ECS) come in a variety of brands and characteristics.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] These chargers vary from 1 kW to 22 kW maximum charge rate.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some use algorithm charge curves, others use constant voltage, constant current.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some are programmable by the end user through a CAN port, some have dials for maximum voltage and amperage, some are preset to specified battery pack voltage, ampere-hour and chemistry.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A 10-ampere-hour battery could take 15 hours to reach a fully charged state from a fully discharged condition with a 1-ampere charger as it would require roughly 1.5 times the battery's capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Public EV charging stations often provide 6 kW (host power of 208 to 240 V AC off a 40-ampere circuit).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] 6 kW will recharge an EV roughly six times faster than 1 kW overnight charging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Rapid charging results in even faster recharge times and is limited only by available AC power, battery type, and the type of charging system.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Power-factor correction (PFC) chargers can more closely approach the maximum current the plug can deliver, shortening charging time.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Project Better Place was deploying a network of charging stations and subsidizing vehicle battery costs through leases and credits until filing for bankruptcy in May 2013.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Most mobile phone chargers are not really chargers, only power adapters that provide a power source for the charging circuitry which is almost always contained within the mobile phone.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some higher-end models feature multiple ports which are equipped with a display which indicates output current.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Some support communication protocols for charging parameters such as Qualcomm Quick Charge or MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Chargers for 12 V automobile auxiliary power outlets may support input voltages of up to 24 or 32 V DC to ensure compatibility, and are sometimes equipped with a display to monitor current or the voltage of the vehicle's electrical system.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] China, the European Union, and other countries are making a national standard on mobile phone chargers using the USB standard.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] In June 2009, 10 of the world's largest mobile phone manufacturers signed a Memorandum of Understanding to develop specifications for and support a microUSB-equipped common external power supply (EPS) for all data-enabled mobile phones sold in the EU.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] On October 22, 2009, the International Telecommunication Union announced that microUSB would be the standard for a universal charger for mobile handsets.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] In October 2022 the EU's Common Charger Directive was approved with the new rules applying to mobile phones and a number of other devices, which came into force in December 2024.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Telecommunications, electric power, and computer uninterruptible power supply facilities may have very large standby battery banks (installed in battery rooms) to maintain critical loads for several hours during interruptions of primary grid power.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Such chargers are permanently installed and equipped with temperature compensation, supervisory alarms for various system faults, and often redundant independent power supplies and redundant rectifier systems.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Chargers for stationary battery plants may have adequate voltage regulation and filtration and sufficient current capacity to allow the battery to be disconnected for maintenance, while the charger supplies the direct current (DC) system load.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The capacity of the charger is specified to maintain the system load and recharge a completely discharged battery within, say, 8 hours or other intervals.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] A properly designed charger can allow batteries to reach their full cycle life.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Excess charging current, lengthy overcharging, or cell reversal in a multiple cell pack cause damage to cells and limit the life expectancy of a battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Most modern cell phones, laptop and tablet computers, and most electric vehicles use lithium-ion batteries.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] These batteries last longest if the battery is frequently charged; fully discharging the cells will degrade their capacity relatively quickly, but most such batteries are used in equipment which can sense the approach of full discharge and discontinue equipment use.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] When stored after charging, lithium battery cells degrade more while fully charged than if they are only 40–50% charged.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] As with all battery types, degradation also occurs faster at higher temperatures.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Degradation in lithium-ion batteries is caused by an increased internal battery resistance often due to the cell oxidation.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] This decreases the efficiency of the battery, resulting in less net current available to be drawn from the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] However, if Li-ion cells are discharged below a certain voltage a chemical reaction occurs that make them dangerous if recharged, which is why many such batteries in consumer goods now have an "electronic fuse" that permanently disables them if the voltage falls below a set level.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] The electronic fuse circuitry draws a small amount of current from the battery, which means that if a laptop battery is left for a long time without charging it, and with a very low initial state of charge, the battery may be permanently destroyed.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Motor vehicles, such as boats, RVs, ATVs, motorcycles, cars, trucks, etc. have used lead–acid batteries.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] These batteries employ a sulfuric acid electrolyte and can generally be charged and discharged without exhibiting memory effect, though sulfation (a chemical reaction in the battery which deposits a layer of sulfates on the lead) will occur over time.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Typically sulfated batteries are simply replaced with new batteries, and the old ones recycled.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Lead–acid batteries will experience substantially longer life when a maintenance charger is used to "float charge" the battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] This prevents the battery from ever being below 100% charge, preventing sulfate from forming.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Proper temperature compensated float voltage should be used to achieve the best results.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Battery charging technology is developing to support the increasing demands of electric vehicles (EVs), consumer electronics, and sustainable energy systems.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Modern chargers may feature Internet of things (IoT) connectivity for real-time monitoring, adaptive charging protocols, remote management, predictive maintenance, and may enhance safety and efficiency.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Artificial intelligence (AI) is being integrated into battery management systems to optimize charging rates, predict battery health, extend usable life, and maximize energy efficiency.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] As a result of electric mobility and smart device proliferation, the global battery charger market is projected (as of 2025) to see significant growth over the following decade.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-charger] Smart chargers integrating IoT, AI, and adaptive features are expected to outpace traditional models globally.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] An **electric battery** is a source of electric power consisting of one or more electrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] When a battery is supplying power, its positive terminal is the cathode and its negative terminal is the anode.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The terminal marked negative is the source of electrons.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] When a battery is connected to an external electric load, those negatively charged electrons flow through the circuit and reach the positive terminal, thus causing a redox reaction by attracting positively charged ions, or cations.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Thus, higher energy reactants are converted to lower energy products, and the free-energy difference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Historically the term "battery" specifically referred to a device composed of multiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a single cell.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Primary (single-use or "disposable") batteries are used once and discarded, as the electrode materials are irreversibly changed during discharge; a common example is the alkaline battery used for flashlights and a multitude of portable electronic devices.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Secondary (rechargeable) batteries can be discharged and recharged multiple times using an applied electric current; the original composition of the electrodes can be restored by reverse current.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Examples include the lead–acid automotive battery used in internal combustion engine vehicles, and lithium-ion batteries used for portable electronics and electric cars.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Batteries come in many shapes and sizes, from miniature cells used to power hearing aids and wristwatches to, at the largest extreme, huge battery banks the size of rooms that provide standby or emergency power for telephone exchanges and computer data centers.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Batteries have much lower specific energy (energy per unit mass) than common fuels such as gasoline.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] In automobiles, this is somewhat offset by the higher efficiency of electric motors in converting electrical energy to mechanical work, compared to combustion engines.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Benjamin Franklin first used the term "battery" in 1749 when he was doing experiments with electricity using a set of linked Leyden jar capacitors.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Franklin grouped a number of the jars into what he described as a "battery", using the military term for weapons functioning together.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] By multiplying the number of holding vessels, a stronger charge could be stored, and more power would be available on discharge.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Italian physicist Alessandro Volta built and described the first electrochemical battery, the voltaic pile, in 1800.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] This was a stack of copper and zinc plates, separated by brine-soaked paper disks, that could produce a steady current for a considerable length of time.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Volta did not understand that the voltage was due to chemical reactions.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] He thought that his cells were an inexhaustible source of energy, and that the associated corrosion effects at the electrodes were a mere nuisance, rather than an unavoidable consequence of their operation, as Michael Faraday showed in 1834.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Although early batteries were of great value for experimental purposes, in practice their voltages fluctuated and they could not provide a large current for a sustained period.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The Daniell cell, invented in 1836 by British chemist John Frederic Daniell, was the first practical source of electricity, becoming an industry standard and seeing widespread adoption as a power source for electrical telegraph networks.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] It consisted of a copper pot filled with a copper sulfate solution, in which was immersed an unglazed earthenware container filled with sulfuric acid and a zinc electrode.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] These wet cells used liquid electrolytes, which were prone to leakage and spillage if not handled correctly.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Many used glass jars to hold their components, which made them fragile and potentially dangerous.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] These characteristics made wet cells unsuitable for portable appliances.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Near the end of the nineteenth century, the invention of dry cell batteries, which replaced the liquid electrolyte with a paste, made portable electrical devices practical.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Batteries in vacuum tube devices historically used a wet cell for the "A" battery (to provide power to the filament) and a dry cell for the "B" battery (to provide the plate voltage).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Between 2010 and 2018, battery demand grew by 30% annually, reaching a total of 180 GWh in 2018.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Conservatively, the growth rate is expected to be maintained at an estimated 25%, culminating in demand reaching 2600 GWh in 2030.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] In addition, cost reductions are expected to further increase the demand to as much as 3562 GWh.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Important reasons for this high rate of growth of the electric battery industry include the electrification of transport, and large-scale deployment in electricity grids, supported by decarbonization initiatives.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Distributed electric batteries, such as those used in battery electric vehicles (vehicle-to-grid) and in home energy storage with smart metering and that are connected to smart grids for demand response are active participants in smart power supply grids.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Secondary use of partially depleted batteries can add to the overall utility of electric batteries by reducing energy storage costs and emission impact due to longer service life.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] In this use, vehicle electric batteries that have their battery capacity reduced to less than 80% (usually after 5–8 years of service) are repurposed for use in backup supplies or renewable energy storage systems.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage envisages the large-scale use of batteries to collect and store energy from the grid or a power plant and then discharge that energy at a later time to provide electricity or other grid services when needed.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage (either turnkey or distributed) are important components of smart power supply grids.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The advent of computational modeling has revolutionized battery materials design, enabling high-throughput screening and atomistic simulations that accelerate the discovery of novel electrolytes and electrodes, moving beyond traditional trial-and-error approaches.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Batteries convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] In many cases, the electrical energy released is the difference in the cohesive or bond energies of the metals, oxides, or molecules undergoing the electrochemical reaction.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] For instance, energy can be stored in Zn or Li, which are high-energy metals because they are not stabilized by d-electron bonding, unlike transition metals.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Batteries are designed so that the energetically favorable redox reaction can occur only when electrons move through the external part of the circuit.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A battery consists of some number of voltaic cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Each cell consists of two half-cells connected in series by a conductive electrolyte containing metal *cations*.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] One half-cell includes electrolyte and the negative electrode, the electrode to which anions (negatively charged ions) migrate; the other half-cell includes electrolyte and the positive electrode, to which cations (positively charged ions) migrate.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Cations are reduced (electrons are added) at the cathode, while metal atoms are oxidized (electrons are removed) at the anode.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Some cells use different electrolytes for each half-cell; then a separator is used to prevent mixing of the electrolytes while allowing ions to flow between half-cells to complete the electrical circuit.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Each half-cell has an electromotive force (*emf*, measured in volts) relative to a standard.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The net emf of the cell is the difference between the emfs of its half-cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Thus, if the electrodes have emfs ${\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}$ , then the net emf is ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}-{\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ ; in other words, the net emf is the difference between the reduction potentials of the half-reactions.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The electrical driving force or $\displaystyle {\Delta V_{\text{bat}}}$ across the terminals of a cell is known as the *terminal voltage (difference)* and is measured in volts.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The terminal voltage of a cell that is neither charging nor discharging is called the open-circuit voltage and equals the emf of the cell.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance, the terminal voltage of a cell that is discharging is smaller in magnitude than the open-circuit voltage and the terminal voltage of a cell that is charging exceeds the open-circuit voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] An ideal cell has negligible internal resistance, so it would maintain a constant terminal voltage of ${\mathcal {E}}$ until exhausted, then dropping to zero.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] If such a cell maintained 1.5 volts and produced a charge of one coulomb then on complete discharge it would have performed 1.5 joules of work.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] In actual cells, the internal resistance increases under discharge and the open-circuit voltage also decreases under discharge.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] If the voltage and resistance are plotted against time, the resulting graphs typically are a curve; the shape of the curve varies according to the chemistry and internal arrangement employed.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The voltage developed across a cell's terminals depends on the energy release of the chemical reactions of its electrodes and electrolyte.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Alkaline and zinc–carbon cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.5 volts; likewise NiCd and NiMH cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.2 volts.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The high electrochemical potential changes in the reactions of lithium compounds give lithium cells emfs of 3 volts or more.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Almost any liquid or moist object that has enough ions to be electrically conductive can serve as the electrolyte for a cell.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] As a novelty or science demonstration, it is possible to insert two electrodes made of different metals into a lemon, potato, etc. and generate small amounts of electricity.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A voltaic pile can be made from two coins (such as a nickel and a penny) and a piece of paper towel dipped in salt water.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Such a pile generates a very low voltage but, when many are stacked in series, they can replace normal batteries for a short time.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Some types of primary batteries used, for example, for telegraph circuits, were restored to operation by replacing the electrodes.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries are not indefinitely rechargeable due to dissipation of the active materials, loss of electrolyte and internal corrosion.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Primary batteries, or primary cells, can produce current immediately on assembly.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] These are most commonly used in portable devices that have low current drain, are used only intermittently, or are used well away from an alternative power source, such as in alarm and communication circuits where other electric power is only intermittently available.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Disposable primary cells cannot be reliably recharged, since the chemical reactions are not easily reversible and active materials may not return to their original forms.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Battery manufacturers recommend against attempting to recharge primary cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] In general, these have higher energy densities than rechargeable batteries, but disposable batteries do not fare well under high-drain applications with loads under 75 ohms (75 Ω).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Common types of disposable batteries include zinc–carbon batteries and alkaline batteries.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries, also known as *secondary cells*, or *rechargeable batteries*, must be charged before first use; they are usually assembled with active materials in the discharged state.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Rechargeable batteries are (re)charged by applying electric current, which reverses the chemical reactions that occur during discharge/use.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Devices to supply the appropriate current are called chargers.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The oldest form of rechargeable battery is the lead–acid battery, which are widely used in automotive and boating applications.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] This technology contains liquid electrolyte in an unsealed container, requiring that the battery be kept upright and the area be well ventilated to ensure safe dispersal of the hydrogen gas it produces during overcharging.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The lead–acid battery is relatively heavy for the amount of electrical energy it can supply.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Its low manufacturing cost and its high surge current levels make it common where its capacity (over approximately 10 Ah) is more important than weight and handling issues.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A common application is the modern car battery, which can, in general, deliver a peak current of 450 amperes.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Many types of electrochemical cells have been produced, with varying chemical processes and designs, including galvanic cells, electrolytic cells, fuel cells, flow cells and voltaic piles.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A *wet cell* battery has a liquid electrolyte.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Other names are *flooded cell*, since the liquid covers all internal parts or *vented cell*, since gases produced during operation can escape to the air.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Wet cells were a precursor to dry cells and are commonly used as a learning tool for electrochemistry.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] They can be built with common laboratory supplies, such as beakers, for demonstrations of how electrochemical cells work.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A particular type of wet cell known as a concentration cell is important in understanding corrosion.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Wet cells may be primary cells (non-rechargeable) or secondary cells (rechargeable).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Originally, all practical primary batteries, such as the Daniell cell, were built as open-top glass jar wet cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Other primary wet cells are the Leclanche cell, Grove cell, Bunsen cell, Chromic acid cell, Clark cell, and Weston cell.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The Leclanche cell chemistry was adapted to the first dry cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Wet cells are still used in automobile batteries and in industry for standby power for switchgear, telecommunication or large uninterruptible power supplies, but in many places batteries with gel cells have been used instead.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] These applications commonly use lead–acid or nickel–cadmium cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Molten salt batteries are primary or secondary batteries that use a molten salt as electrolyte.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] They operate at high temperatures and must be well insulated to retain heat.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A *dry cell* uses a paste electrolyte, with only enough moisture to allow current to flow.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Unlike a wet cell, a dry cell can operate in any orientation without spilling, as it contains no free liquid, making it suitable for portable equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] By comparison, the first wet cells were typically fragile glass containers with lead rods hanging from the open top and needed careful handling to avoid spillage.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries did not achieve the safety and portability of the dry cell until the development of the gel battery.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A common dry cell is the zinc–carbon battery, sometimes called the dry Leclanché cell, with a nominal voltage of 1.5 volts, the same as the alkaline battery (since both use the same zinc–manganese dioxide combination).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A standard dry cell comprises a zinc anode, usually in the form of a cylindrical pot, with a carbon cathode in the form of a central rod.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The electrolyte is ammonium chloride in the form of a paste next to the zinc anode.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The remaining space between the electrolyte and carbon cathode is taken up by a second paste consisting of ammonium chloride and manganese dioxide, the latter acting as a depolariser.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] In some designs, the ammonium chloride is replaced by zinc chloride.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A reserve battery can be stored unassembled (unactivated and supplying no power) for a long period (perhaps years).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] When the battery is needed, then it is assembled (e.g., by adding electrolyte); once assembled, the battery is charged and ready to work.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] For example, a battery for an electronic artillery fuze might be activated by the impact of firing a gun.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The acceleration breaks a capsule of electrolyte that activates the battery and powers the fuze's circuits.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Reserve batteries are usually designed for a short service life (seconds or minutes) after long storage (years).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A water-activated battery for oceanographic instruments or military applications becomes activated on immersion in water.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The solid-state battery is also said to have "three times the energy density", increasing its useful life in electric vehicles, for example.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] It should also be more ecologically sound since the technology uses less expensive, earth-friendly materials such as sodium extracted from seawater.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Sony has developed a biological battery that generates electricity from sugar in a way that is similar to the processes observed in living organisms.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The battery generates electricity through the use of enzymes that break down carbohydrates.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The sealed valve regulated lead–acid battery (VRLA battery) is popular in the automotive industry as a replacement for the lead–acid wet cell.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The VRLA battery uses an immobilized sulfuric acid electrolyte, reducing the chance of leakage and extending shelf life.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] VRLA batteries immobilize the electrolyte.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Other portable rechargeable batteries include several sealed "dry cell" types, that are useful in applications such as mobile phones and laptop computers.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Cells of this type (in order of increasing power density and cost) include nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–zinc (NiZn), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), and lithium-ion (Li-ion) cells.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Li-ion has by far the highest share of the dry cell rechargeable market.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] NiMH has replaced NiCd in most applications due to its higher capacity, but NiCd remains in use in power tools, two-way radios, and medical equipment.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Low self-discharge (LSD) allows secondary cells to be charged prior to shipping.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Lithium–sulfur batteries were used on the longest and highest solar-powered flight.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Batteries of all types are manufactured in consumer and industrial grades.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Standard-format batteries are inserted into battery holder in the device that uses them.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] When a device does not uses standard-format batteries, they are typically combined into a custom battery pack which holds multiple batteries in addition to features such as a battery management system and battery isolator which ensure that the batteries within are charged and discharged evenly.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Primary batteries readily available to consumers range from tiny button cells used for electric watches, to the No.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] 6 cell used for signal circuits or other long duration applications.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Secondary cells are made in very large sizes; very large batteries can power a submarine or stabilize an electrical grid and help level out peak loads.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] As of 2017, the world's largest battery was built in South Australia by Tesla.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A battery in Hebei Province, China, which can store 36 MWh of electricity was built in 2013 at a cost of $500 million.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Another large battery, composed of Ni–Cd cells, was in Fairbanks, Alaska.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] It covered 2,000 square metres (22,000 sq ft)—bigger than a football pitch—and weighed 1,300 tonnes.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] It was manufactured by ABB to provide backup power in the event of a blackout.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The battery can provide 40 MW of power for up to seven minutes.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Sodium–sulfur batteries have been used to store wind power.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A 4.4 MWh battery system that can deliver 11 MW for 25 minutes stabilizes the output of the Auwahi wind farm in Hawaii.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Many important cell properties, such as voltage, energy density, flammability, available cell constructions, operating temperature range and shelf life, are dictated by battery chemistry.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A battery's characteristics may vary over load cycle, over charge cycle, and over lifetime due to many factors including internal chemistry, current drain, and temperature.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] At low temperatures, a battery cannot deliver as much power.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] As such, in cold climates, some car owners install battery warmers, which are small electric heating pads that keep the car battery warm.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A battery's *capacity* is the amount of electric charge it can deliver at a voltage that does not drop below the specified terminal voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The more electrode material contained in the cell the greater its capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] A small cell has less capacity than a larger cell with the same chemistry, although they develop the same open-circuit voltage.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Capacity is usually stated in ampere-hours (A·h) (mAh for small batteries).
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The rated capacity of a battery is usually expressed as the product of 20 hours multiplied by the current that a new battery can consistently supply for 20 hours at 20 °C (68 °F), while remaining above a specified terminal voltage per cell.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 100 A·h can deliver 5 A over a 20-hour period at room temperature.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The fraction of the stored charge that a battery can deliver depends on multiple factors, including battery chemistry, the rate at which the charge is delivered (current), the required terminal voltage, the storage period, ambient temperature and other factors.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The higher the discharge rate, the lower the capacity.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] is the capacity when discharged at a rate of 1 amp.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] is the amount of time (in hours) that a battery can sustain.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] Charged batteries (rechargeable or disposable) lose charge by internal self-discharge over time although not discharged, due to the presence of generally irreversible *side reactions* that consume charge carriers without producing current.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] The rate of self-discharge depends upon battery chemistry and construction, typically from months to years for significant loss.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] When batteries are recharged, additional side reactions reduce capacity for subsequent discharges.
[src:ac-adapter/battery-electricity] After enough recharges, in essence all capacity is lost and the battery stops producing power.
